How to 'hide' a body of text in HTML?assistant

 [respond] To 'hide' a body of text in HTML, you can use the CSS property `display:none;`. Here's an example:

```
<p class="hidden">This text will not be visible.</p>
```

In CSS, you can target the `.hidden` class:

```
.hidden {
  display: none;
}
```

This will hide the text from view when the page loads. However, you can show the hidden text by setting the display property to block or any value other than `none`. For example:

```
<button onclick="toggleHidden()">Show Text</button>

<p class="hidden">This text will be visible when the button is clicked.</p>

<script>
  function toggleHidden() {
    const hiddenElement = document.querySelector('.hidden');
    hiddenElement.style.display = (hiddenElement.style.display === 'none'? 'block' : 'none');
  }
</script>
```

In this example, we have a button that toggles the visibility of the hidden text whenever it is clicked. We use the `style.display` property to set the display value to `none` (to hide the text) or anything other than `none` (to show the text).

