How to hide a dead link on a webpage?assistant

 [respond] To hide a dead link on a webpage, you can use JavaScript to remove the link or make it hidden. Here's an example:

1. Add the following CSS to hide the link by default:

```
.hidden-link {
  display: none;
}
```

2. Add the class "hidden-link" to the link element:

```
<a id="dead-link" href="http://broken-link.com" class="hidden-link">Dead Link</a>
```

3. Use JavaScript to remove the class from the link element and re-add the CSS declaration as a data attribute to the link:

```
<script>
  var link = document.getElementById('dead-link');
  link.addEventListener('transitionend', function(event) {
    if (event.propertyName === 'visibility') {
      var originalStyle = link.getAttribute('data-style');
      link.setAttribute('style', originalStyle);
    }
  });

  link.style.color = '#ff00ff';
  link.style.textDecoration = 'underline';
  link.style.transition = 'visibility 0s ease';
  link.style.translateZ(1000);
  link.dispatchEvent(new Event('transitionend'));
</script>
```

4. Save and publish the page.

The dead link will now be hidden by default, but when the page loads, the JavaScript will remove the class and add the styling to make the link visible. The link will be highlighted and underlined to indicate that it's a dead link.
